Russia crossed
the brightest red line in
international law

15:11.944 --> 15:18.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by invading and annexing Crimea
and then dividing
Eastern Ukraine in the Donbass,
and, of course,

15:18.050 --> 15:21.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has been threatening our allies
the Baltic
states.

15:21.087 --> 15:26.893 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those sanction regimes are in
place by Europeans,
Canadians and Americans as
leverage against

15:26.926 --> 15:28.694 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Russia.

15:28.728 --> 15:32.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the sanctions cannot be
lifted until Russia
removes its forces from Eastern
Ukraine.

15:32.198 --> 15:37.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If it doesn't do that, and if we
give away
on sanctions, Russia gets away
with grand

15:37.236 --> 15:39.005 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
larceny.

15:39.038 --> 15:43.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The European leadership will be
furious with
the United States, Angela Merkel
especially.

15:43.242 --> 15:47.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She negotiated these sanctions
with President
Putin directly.

15:47.079 --> 15:48.881 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so I think it's very unwise.

15:48.915 --> 15:51.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It gives away American
influence.

15:51.250 --> 15:55.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It would be a weak policy by the
United States,
not a strong policy.

15:55.822 --> 16:01.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Heather Conley, is
this sort of
essentially offering to accept
this annexation

16:01.227 --> 16:03.529 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Crimea in exchange for
something else?

16:03.563 --> 16:05.198 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is this sort of like a business
deal?

16:05.231 --> 16:06.332 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HEATHER CONLEY: Well, exactly.

16:06.365 --> 16:08.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're talking about two separate
things.

16:08.134 --> 16:12.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The sanctions relate to the
annexation of
Crimea and the invasion of
Eastern Ukraine.

16:12.338 --> 16:16.142 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A nuclear arms agreement --
let's step back
a minute.

16:16.175 --> 16:19.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russia has been in violation of
the IMF Treaty
many years.

16:19.879 --> 16:22.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, steps have not been taken
to address
those violations.

16:22.915 --> 16:29.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We have seen where --
announcements of moving
of Russian tactical weapons near
NATO borders,

16:29.822 --> 16:31.724 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
near now U.S. troops.

16:31.757 --> 16:32.992 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We do need to address this.

16:33.025 --> 16:36.329 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But we're mixing apples and
oranges here.

16:36.362 --> 16:42.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, nuclear stability, I
agree, is very
important, but, right now -- and
I thought

16:42.268 --> 16:47.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
president-elect Trump had
mentioned that he
wants to strengthen America's
nuclear arsenal.

16:47.139 --> 16:48.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Perhaps I misunderstood.

16:48.374 --> 16:49.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, are we reducing?

16:49.942 --> 16:51.344 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Are we increasing?

16:51.377 --> 16:54.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we have to watch very
carefully Russia's
military modernization.

16:54.213 --> 16:59.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are actually increasing
their strategic
nuclear deterrent.

16:59.919 --> 17:03.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They may be at a point where
they're accelerating
that program.

17:03.155 --> 17:04.957 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have to be extremely mindful.

17:04.991 --> 17:07.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is protecting U.S. national
security.

17:07.860 --> 17:15.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Russia, as General Mattis
noted, really
is a near-term threat, could be
an existential

17:15.635 --> 17:17.503 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
threat.

17:17.536 --> 17:20.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So let's keep our eye on the
prize here, and
not start conflating two very
different things.

17:20.873 --> 17:26.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Nicholas Burns,
talked about this
equating Vladimir Putin and
Angela Merkel.

17:26.112 --> 17:27.713 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's your take on that?

17:27.747 --> 17:30.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HEATHER CONLEY: I -- to be
honest with you,
that was the most -- I'm sorry,
Nic.

17:30.683 --> 17:31.651 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

17:31.684 --> 17:32.652 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN YANG: Sorry.

17:32.685 --> 17:33.886 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Go ahead, Mr. Ambassador.

17:33.920 --> 17:36.923 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICHOLAS BURNS: Sorry, just the
time delay.

17:36.956 --> 17:40.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I just wanted to say, Angela
Merkel is our
strongest ally.

17:40.192 --> 17:42.561 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Vladimir Putin is our greatest
adversary.

17:42.595 --> 17:45.898 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
To equate them is an insult to
Angela Merkel.

17:45.932 --> 17:51.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Europe is our largest trade
partner, largest
investor into our economy and
largest ally.

17:51.504 --> 17:53.239 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Europe really matters.

17:53.272 --> 17:56.042 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Donald Trump says we're
indifferent to the
future of the E.U.?

17:56.075 --> 18:00.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The E.U. was formed to put aside
war between
France and Germany and unite
Europe in peace.

18:00.813 --> 18:01.847 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's done that.

18:01.881 --> 18:02.882 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We should support it.

18:02.915 --> 18:04.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: We have got less than
a minute
left.

18:04.550 --> 18:06.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mr. Ambassador, let's start with
you.

18:06.285 --> 18:11.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What -- overall, what does this
say about
what's ahead for U.S.-European
relations?

18:12.024 --> 18:17.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICHOLAS BURNS: A very rocky
start for the
administration of Donald Trump.

18:17.129 --> 18:22.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have to believe that Rex
Tillerson, the
new secretary of state incoming,
Jim Mattis,

18:22.702 --> 18:26.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the new secretary of defense,
they understand
the value of NATO.

18:26.072 --> 18:27.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They understand that we're the
leader of the
West.

18:27.807 --> 18:32.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I hope very much that Donald
Trump will
agree with them and shift these
positions.

18:32.311 --> 18:34.814 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But, Heather Conley,
who's speaking
for the administration?

18:34.847 --> 18:36.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HEATHER CONLEY: That's the
question.

18:36.482 --> 18:39.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we're going to need to get
some clarification
on that.

18:39.518 --> 18:45.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just to underscore it, European
solidarity,
unity -- it is an incredibly
important trade

18:45.424 --> 18:47.393 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and investment partner to the
U.S.

18:47.426 --> 18:52.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We cannot want Europe to be
divided, to be
-- to fall apart.

18:52.431 --> 18:54.967 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're too important to U.S.
national security.

18:55.001 --> 18:59.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Seventy years ago, another great
secretary
of state and defense, George C.
Marshall,

18:59.772 --> 19:02.208 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
made his Marshall Plan.

19:02.241 --> 19:04.410 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This was a massive investment in
Europe.

19:04.443 --> 19:06.946 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The United States has invested
in Europe.

19:06.979 --> 19:08.748 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We are the beneficiaries of it.

19:08.781 --> 19:10.449 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We cannot let this go away.

19:10.483 --> 19:11.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's too important.

19:11.917 --> 19:15.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Heather Conley,
Nicholas Burns,
thank you both very much.

19:15.354 --> 19:22.361 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HEATHER CONLEY: Thank you.

