for the U.K. to exit the
European Union.

37:50.301 --> 37:54.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there are obstacles in the
government's
way, like John Shaw and Wynne
Edwards.

37:54.339 --> 37:59.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They lead a group of British
expatriates living
in France who want to delay or
defeat Brexit

37:59.644 --> 38:01.412 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
altogether.

38:01.446 --> 38:04.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WYNNE EDWARDS, Opposes Brexit:
It affects
us profusely, because we have
made our lives

38:04.382 --> 38:05.350 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
there.

38:05.383 --> 38:07.152 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We have invested there.

38:07.185 --> 38:11.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if we are made to leave or
if we don't
enjoy the rights there that we
enjoy at the

38:11.289 --> 38:13.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
moment, it would severely affect
us.

38:13.625 --> 38:19.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: The U.N.
estimates 1.2 million
U.K.-born people live in other
E.U. countries,

38:19.797 --> 38:21.799 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
which give them the same rights
as any European.

38:21.833 --> 38:23.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN SHAW, Opposes Brexit: I
have got a right
to work.

38:23.701 --> 38:25.470 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have a right to living there
forever.

38:25.503 --> 38:27.105 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have got a right of owning
property.

38:27.138 --> 38:32.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I got a right of transferring my
property
to my family when I die.

38:32.544 --> 38:35.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have got have a right of use
of health care.

38:35.146 --> 38:41.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of these are rights which
are conferred
on me as a result of living in
the E.U.

38:41.319 --> 38:47.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: But Brexit
would likely end
those rights, so Fair Deal for
Expats and

38:47.125 --> 38:51.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
others have taken their case to
the British
court system to argue that only
Parliament

38:51.896 --> 38:53.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
can call for a break with the
E.U.

38:53.831 --> 39:02.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The government says the Brexit
referendum
gives it the right to decide how
Britain exits.

39:02.073 --> 39:06.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those from other European
countries living
in the U.K. are also watching
anxiously for

39:06.444 --> 39:08.313 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the results.

39:08.346 --> 39:12.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are so many French here
that London
is called Paris on the Thames,
and is considered

39:12.517 --> 39:15.486 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the sixth largest city in
France.

39:15.520 --> 39:19.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Patricia Connell, founder of
France in London,
says that's why Parliament
should be the one

39:19.490 --> 39:21.859 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to decide if and how Brexit
happens.

39:21.893 --> 39:23.661 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PATRICIA CONNELL, Founder,
France in London:
There should be a discussion.

39:23.695 --> 39:29.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there should be debates in
the House of
Commons about it and how it
should be done.

39:29.100 --> 39:34.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that that is that
point that is
being argued at the moment about
the triggering

39:34.239 --> 39:36.207 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of Article 50.

39:36.241 --> 39:43.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Without Parliament debating and
agreeing on
it and without a vote taking
place, then it

39:43.348 --> 39:45.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shouldn't be triggered.

39:45.183 --> 39:48.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: In November,
the high court
ruled in the opponents' favor,
saying that

39:48.486 --> 39:50.922 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Parliament indeed should be
involved.

39:50.955 --> 39:54.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now the British government is
appealing to
the Supreme Court.

39:54.692 --> 39:59.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Parliament member Anne-Marie
Trevelyan campaigned
in favor of Brexit and says,
just because

39:59.297 --> 40:04.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the popular vote was close, with
52 percent
in favor, doesn't mean it should
be discarded.

40:04.135 --> 40:06.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE-MARIE TREVELYAN, Member of
Parliament:
I wasn't terribly thrilled when
Tony Blair

40:06.838 --> 40:09.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
got elected as prime minister,
but I didn't
suddenly call for a second
referendum and

40:09.674 --> 40:11.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
say that the people were wrong.

40:11.142 --> 40:14.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If a majority -- you know, it's
a simple equation.

40:14.145 --> 40:17.115 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If it's a majority decision,
then that's the
decision we go with.

40:17.148 --> 40:18.883 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's how democracies work.

40:18.916 --> 40:22.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Trevelyan says,
no matter
how the Supreme Court rules,
she's confident

40:22.920 --> 40:26.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the outcome will be the
same, with Britain
eventually leaving the E.U.

40:26.924 --> 40:30.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE-MARIE TREVELYAN: Coming out
of the E.U.
will ensure that we're not stuck
in a very,

40:30.194 --> 40:34.899 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very sluggish customs union, but
we're able
to be the greatest free trade
nation on Earth

40:34.932 --> 40:36.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
again, which is what so many
people want.

40:36.801 --> 40:41.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you talk to businesses, they
want to be
freed of the regulations and of
the drag pressures

40:41.606 --> 40:44.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that being stuck within the E.U.
trading bloc
creates.

40:44.676 --> 40:49.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: But it's not at
all clear
exactly how businesses would be
affected.

40:49.314 --> 40:53.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
East London's Canary Wharf is
home to some
of the world's largest banks.

40:53.951 --> 40:58.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Brexit would likely mean tighter
trading rules
with Europe, and that has some
thinking about

40:58.356 --> 41:00.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
moving out of the U.K.

41:00.792 --> 41:04.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Billions of dollars a day are
traded here,
making London the biggest
financial center

41:04.462 --> 41:05.563 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the world.

41:05.596 --> 41:07.432 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But Brexit could change that.

41:07.465 --> 41:12.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And cities like Frankfurt, Paris
and Dublin
are all vying for possible
business as banks

41:12.704 --> 41:16.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
consider leaving.

41:16.841 --> 41:22.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Market strategist Mike Ingram
says financial
services in Britain employ about
2.2 million

41:22.513 --> 41:26.351 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people, accounting for 12
percent of the country's
GDP.

41:26.384 --> 41:28.119 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That won't be easy to move.

41:28.152 --> 41:32.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE INGRAM, Market Strategist:
But, at the
end of the day, you cannot
deconstruct what

41:32.357 --> 41:37.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is on paper one of the most
important financial
centers in the world overnight.

41:37.729 --> 41:44.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, let's say we go to
Dublin, low tax
rate, they speak English, right
time zone,

41:44.102 --> 41:45.336 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
et cetera.

41:45.370 --> 41:47.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Physically, how do you how do
you decamp that
many people?

41:48.005 --> 41:52.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Wynne Edwards
says an even
more critical concern is the
instability to

41:52.677 --> 41:54.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Europe in general.

41:54.746 --> 41:59.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
World Wars I and II, in fact,
wars going back
to centuries, have set nation
against nation

41:59.951 --> 42:01.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on the continent.

42:01.285 --> 42:04.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He worries breaking apart the
union will foster
more strife.

42:04.188 --> 42:08.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WYNNE EDWARDS: I think you need
to cast your
mind back to what's happened in
history.

42:08.459 --> 42:14.832 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And just, without going into it,
I cannot
believe that anyone wouldn't
want a united

42:14.866 --> 42:16.768 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Europe.

42:16.801 --> 42:19.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE-MARIE TREVELYAN: I would
disagree, that
I think a dangerous Europe is
one where nations

42:19.404 --> 42:27.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
feel suffocated by the E.U.
machine, which
is trying to overcome and stop
those individual

42:27.645 --> 42:29.514 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
nations' views of the world.

42:29.547 --> 42:32.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: The Supreme
Court is expected
to rule this month.

42:32.950 --> 42:37.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whatever it decides, Britain
will remain divided
about whether Brexit will
benefit or hurt

42:37.088 --> 42:38.856 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the country.

42:38.890 --> 42:43.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For each side, the clock is
ticking, towards
implementing Brexit, limiting
the upheaval

42:43.261 --> 42:45.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it could cause, or stopping it
altogether.

42:45.963 --> 42:54.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Jennifer Glasse
in London.

42:54.972 --> 43:09.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Student loan debt
is an issue
facing many Americans, and can
take years

43:09.153 --> 43:10.855 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to pay off.

43:10.888 --> 43:15.259 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In particular, the problems some
students
face at for-profit schools are
getting closer

43:15.293 --> 43:16.661 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
scrutiny.

43:16.694 --> 43:19.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marketplace's Lizzie O'Leary has
the story.

43:19.197 --> 43:22.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of our series How the
Deck Is Stacked.

43:22.266 --> 43:27.438 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's in partnership with
"Frontline" and Marketplace,
and funded by the Corporation
for Public Broadcasting.

43:27.472 --> 43:32.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: Before she
became a mother,
New Yorker Danielle Adorno (ph)
dreamed of

43:32.176 --> 43:34.011 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
working as a pastry chef.

43:34.045 --> 43:38.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When she came across ads for the
Art Institute
of New York, it seemed like a
great fit.

43:38.950 --> 43:41.419 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And she says school
administrators promised
her a lot.

43:41.452 --> 43:44.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIELLE LOPEZ, Student Loan
Borrower: They
were very adamant on like their
job placement

43:44.622 --> 43:51.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rates, boasting over like 90
percent job placement,
boasting about their chef
instructors working

43:51.329 --> 43:53.965 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at Nobu and all these high-end
restaurants.

43:53.998 --> 43:58.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You would think, oh, OK, I'm
going to get
the quality education that I'm
looking for,

43:58.870 --> 44:00.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because that's what it's about,
quality.

44:00.671 --> 44:04.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, I figure, if I'm going
to pay that
much -- that amount of money for
such a short

44:04.275 --> 44:06.611 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
program, I'm going to be getting
something
out of it.

44:06.644 --> 44:08.246 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that wasn't what happened.

44:08.279 --> 44:11.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: She claims the
school never
helped her get work in her
field.

44:11.649 --> 44:15.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she says employers don't
value the degree
in the way she thought they
would.

44:15.920 --> 44:18.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's no longer paying her loan
company her
$25,000 debt.

44:18.956 --> 44:22.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIELLE LOPEZ: They don't
deserve a single
penny out of me, because I
didn't get the

44:22.493 --> 44:23.895 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
education I paid for.

44:23.928 --> 44:26.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: You did sign a
contract when
you took out that money.

44:26.764 --> 44:28.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DANIELLE LOPEZ: I did.

44:28.566 --> 44:33.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I also thought if -- I feel
like it stopped
being about education and
started becoming

44:33.237 --> 44:34.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about consumerism.

44:34.839 --> 44:36.474 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm paying you for a service.

44:36.507 --> 44:37.775 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I paid you for an education.

44:37.808 --> 44:39.477 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I paid you to train me.

44:39.510 --> 44:43.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I paid you to give me this 90
percent job
placement rate that you boasted
about.

44:43.114 --> 44:44.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You told me you were going to
place me in
a job.

44:45.016 --> 44:46.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, instead, I got a program
that was shutting
down.

44:46.784 --> 44:51.188 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: The Art
Institute's parent
company, Education Management
Corporation,

44:51.222 --> 44:53.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was the target of a federal
investigation.

44:53.958 --> 44:58.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Department of Justice officials
say the company
acted as a recruitment mill.

44:58.362 --> 45:02.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It reached a $95.5 million false
claims settlement.

45:02.500 --> 45:04.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But there was no determination
of liability.

45:04.669 --> 45:08.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LORETTA LYNCH, U.S. Attorney
General: This
kind of abuse hurts not only
taxpayers, but

45:08.639 --> 45:10.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
also the students.

45:10.608 --> 45:14.946 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: The Art
Institute of New York's
Web site says it is no longer
accepting students.

45:14.979 --> 45:18.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the campus has been put on
probation by
their accreditor.

45:18.816 --> 45:24.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the last few years, the Obama
administration
put many new regulations in
place to address

45:24.055 --> 45:27.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
aggressive marketing and job
placement claims
by several for-profit schools.

45:27.892 --> 45:31.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States:
Too many of these for-profit
colleges -- some

45:31.929 --> 45:37.201 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do a fine job, but many of them
recruit kids
in.

45:37.234 --> 45:40.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The kids don't graduate, but
they're left
with the debt.

45:40.471 --> 45:44.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: Earlier this
month, the Department
of Education released a report
saying many

45:44.742 --> 45:49.814 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for-profit graduates aren't
earning enough
to reasonably repay their loans.

45:49.847 --> 45:54.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One out of four career training
programs are
at risk of losing their federal
funding.

45:54.719 --> 46:01.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The University of Phoenix has
215,000 students,
the largest for-profit college
in the country.

46:01.092 --> 46:06.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Stephen Trimble was 27 years old
when he decided
to take classes at the
University of Phoenix

46:06.263 --> 46:07.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
outside Philadelphia.

46:07.665 --> 46:09.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN TRIMBLE, Student Loan
Borrower: I
didn't have a degree.

46:09.433 --> 46:16.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I thought that getting one
would allow
me to advance in my career
better, faster.

46:16.173 --> 46:17.908 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It would allow me to earn more
money.

46:17.942 --> 46:22.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: Trimble took out
a private
loan for $30,000 in 2008 to
study business

46:23.014 --> 46:27.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
management, but dropped out
before finishing,
and then fell behind on his
payments.

46:27.618 --> 46:29.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He says that had a domino
effect.

46:29.553 --> 46:32.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN TRIMBLE: It's decimated
my financial
life.

46:32.990 --> 46:37.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My credit score is probably 150
to 200 points
lower than it should be.

46:37.561 --> 46:40.865 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I couldn't get a mortgage if I
wanted one.

46:40.898 --> 46:42.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
My house is in my wife's name.

46:42.867 --> 46:46.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: Trimble and
Adorno are part
of the group of Americans who
turned to for-profits

46:46.904 --> 46:48.673 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
schools during the great
recession.

46:48.706 --> 46:52.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SANDY BAUM, Urban Institute:
There was very
rapid growth in the for-profit
sector, much

46:52.309 --> 46:53.878 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of it big companies.

46:53.911 --> 46:57.581 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The University of Phoenix is a
prime example.

46:57.615 --> 47:01.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They signed up all kinds of
people who had
no idea what they were getting
into.

47:01.352 --> 47:03.154 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, that's a problem.

47:03.187 --> 47:06.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LIZZIE O'LEARY: Finishing school
is a challenge
for many students enrolled in
these kinds

47:06.457 --> 47:10.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of programs, according to Sandy
Baum, a senior
fellow at the Urban Institute.

47:10.294 --> 47:14.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SANDY BAUM: On average, people
who go to for-profit
institutions are much more
likely to borrow,

47:14.365 --> 47:18.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to borrow more, and not to be
able to repay
their loans.

47:18.602 --> 47:24.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's pretty clear from the data
that the crisis
is centered around people who
start college

47:24.508 --> 47:25.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
