50:28.125 --> 50:40.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight:
What we can
learn about life from those
facing death?

50:40.304 --> 50:45.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chaplain Kerry Egan's new book
is called "On
Living" and is the latest
edition in our essay

50:45.576 --> 50:47.678 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
series In My Humble Opinion.

50:47.711 --> 50:52.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KERRY EGAN, Author, "On Living":
When people
learn that I'm a hospice
chaplain, they usually

50:52.650 --> 50:55.219 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
have one of two reactions.

50:55.252 --> 51:00.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They either say they could never
do that job
and change the subject
completely, or they

51:00.524 --> 51:03.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
have questions, lots of
questions.

51:03.627 --> 51:07.464 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the questions I hear more
often than
I would have thought is about
people's last

51:07.498 --> 51:09.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
words.

51:09.266 --> 51:14.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People are enormously curious
about what people
who are actively dying talk
about.

51:14.038 --> 51:16.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Have you ever heard anything
really amazing?

51:16.941 --> 51:20.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's the craziest deathbed
confession you
have ever heard?

51:20.311 --> 51:23.314 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Should I plan out my last words?

51:23.347 --> 51:28.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That last question seemed really
odd to me
the first time someone asked,
but I have been

51:28.118 --> 51:33.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
asked it at least a dozen times,
so it's obviously
on some people's minds.

51:33.457 --> 51:38.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The questions don't actually
match up with
what typically happens when
someone is dying.

51:38.062 --> 51:44.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, I suspect they're
coming from a sort
of Hollywood movie or television
idea of what

51:44.501 --> 51:52.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dying should be like, clean,
calm, bizarrely
romantic, always with the good
sense to close

51:52.376 --> 51:59.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
your eyes before taking a long
sigh and limply
tossing your head to the side,
and beautiful,

51:59.817 --> 52:02.519 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
urgent, life-altering
utterances.

52:02.553 --> 52:09.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if this is what you think
happens in death,
I can see how you would feel a
lot of pressure

52:09.360 --> 52:12.096 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to get it right.

52:12.129 --> 52:17.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When someone asks me if they
should plan their
last words, the short answer is:
No.

52:17.968 --> 52:21.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People who are dying are often
unconscious
for days before they die.

52:21.205 --> 52:22.873 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Sometimes, they're in pain.

52:22.906 --> 52:24.808 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're often highly medicated.

52:24.842 --> 52:32.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Honestly, most of the last words
I have heard
are so mundane, I can't even
give an example.

52:32.316 --> 52:36.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
When you know you have a
terminal diagnosis,
death often takes a person by
surprise.

52:36.987 --> 52:42.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You might not even know that
your last words
are your last words.

52:42.159 --> 52:46.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there's a longer, more
complex answer
too.

52:46.063 --> 52:50.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If you had something so
important to tell
your loved ones that you feel
the need to

52:50.401 --> 52:55.739 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plan out what to say, then why
would you wait
to say it?

52:55.773 --> 53:02.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If it's so important that you're
worried about
it now, then say it now.

53:02.146 --> 53:04.715 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Ask for forgiveness now.

53:04.748 --> 53:07.117 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Say you love someone now.

53:07.151 --> 53:11.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Share whatever wisdom you have
with the world
right now.

53:11.822 --> 53:13.924 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Here's the thing.

53:13.957 --> 53:20.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When people ask me about dying
words, what
they're really asking is, what
is so important

53:20.998 --> 53:26.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in this life that it should be
the very last
thing we talk about?

53:26.136 --> 53:33.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, instead of asking, what do
other people
talk about, ask yourself, what
do I really

53:33.410 --> 53:37.147 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
want to talk about now?

53:37.181 --> 53:40.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that's a really good
question.

53:40.084 --> 53:42.219 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's a really good thing to
ponder.

